Tips to extract data straight from an excel file extracted using ehints.

Preparation work

Step 1: Enter data into a designated textbox in Edoc. Standardize data entry using “acronym expansion” or a EXCEL template. Ensure that outcome values are within brackets/braces

Step 2: Use EHINTS to extract and save data as an EXCEL or csv file

Step 3: Download R software & Rstudio

Step 4: Open RStudio.

Start using RStudio

Step 5: Set working directory

Step 6: Load/install R packages

# load R packages and install them if they are missing
for (i in c("readxl", "stringr", "dplyr")) {
    if (!require(i, character.only = TRUE)) {
        install.packages(i, dependencies = TRUE)
        library(i, character.only = TRUE)
    }
}

# library(stringr); library(dplyr) ## if packages are already installed in R

Data extraction

Step 7: Read the csv file
* Use the readxl package to read EXCEL files
* Use the excel.link or XLconnect packages to read password-protected EXCEL files. Details

acl <- read.csv("ACL csv 2.csv")
# acl <- read.csv("C:/Users/SGH/Dropbox/HUATAR ABC/ALPHA/ACL data extraction files/Markdown file/ACL csv 2.csv")

Download a copy of the toy dataset

Step 8: Make headers lowercase to make life (a little) easier

names(acl) <- tolower(make.names(names(acl), unique=TRUE))

Step 9a: Select columns that you are interested in

#pt.id and value.text are headers of columns of interest
acl2 <- dplyr::select(acl, "pt.id", "value.text")

Step 9b: Select rows that you are interested in

# str_which() identifies row numbers of cells containing :"Extension Flexion ROM (...)"  
row_numbers_with_values <- str_which(acl$value.text, "Extension Flexion ROM\\s\\(")

acl2 <- acl2  %>%  
  slice ( row_numbers_with_values )  
  
# acl2 <- slice(acl2, 8,16,24)
# 8,16,24 are row numbers

Step 10: Extract everything that is within brackets

# .   # match any character
# *   # zero or more times
# ?   # matching as few characters as possible
outcome1 <- str_extract_all(acl2$value.text, "(?<=\\().*?(?=\\))")

Step 11: Create table from extracted data

outcome2 <- data.frame(do.call(rbind, outcome1))

Step 12: Select columns that are of interest

outcome2 <- dplyr::select(outcome2, X1:X3, X5:X7, X9:X11, X13:X15)

Step 13: Extract patient identifiers

ptid <-dplyr::select(acl2,"pt.id")

Step 14: Merge 2 tables

ptid_with_outcomes <- dplyr::bind_cols(ptid,outcome2)

# ptid_with_outcomes <- outcome2 %>%  
#   mutate(ptid = acl2%>% pull(pt.id)) %>%

Step 15: Rename headers

final <- ptid_with_outcomes %>% 
  dplyr::rename(
    ax_date = X1,
    extension_range = X2,
    flexion_range = X3,
    knee_extension_uninvolved = X5,

    leg_press_uninvolved = X13,
    leg_press_involved = X14,
    leg_press_LSI = X15)

Export extracted data as csv file

Final step: Export as a excel file to share it with others 👋

write.csv(final, "the_data_i_painstakingly_extracted_using_r.csv",row.names=FALSE, na="NA")

TL;DR

Just the R codes, please

# load the libraries and install them if they are missing
for (i in c("readxl", "stringr", "dplyr")) {
  if(! require(i, character.only = TRUE)){
    install.packages(i, dependencies = TRUE)
    library(i, character.only=TRUE)}
}


acl <- read.csv("ACL csv 2.csv")
names(acl) <- tolower(make.names(names(acl), unique=TRUE))
row_numbers_with_values <- str_which(acl$value.text, "Extension Flexion ROM\\s\\(")

acl2 <- acl %>%  
  slice ( row_numbers_with_values ) %>%  
  dplyr::select(pt.id, value.text)

# .   # match any character
# *   # zero or more times
# ?   # matching as few characters as possible
outcome1 <- str_extract_all(acl2$value.text, "(?<=\\().*?(?=\\))")
outcome1
outcome2 <- data.frame(do.call(rbind, outcome1))
outcome2 <- select(outcome2, X1:X3, X5:X7, X9:X11, X13:X15)


ptid <-select(acl2,"pt.id")
datatable(ptid)
ptid_with_outcomes <- dplyr::bind_cols(ptid,outcome2)
# ptid_with_outcomes <- outcome2 %>%  
#   mutate(ptid = acl2%>% pull(pt.id)) %>%  
#   dplyr::select(ptid, everything())

final <- ptid_with_outcomes %>% 
  dplyr::rename(
    ax_date = X1,
    extension_range = X2,
    flexion_range = X3,
    knee_extension_uninvolved = X5,
    knee_extension_involved = X6,
    knee_extension_LSI = X7,
    hamstring_curl_uninvolved = X9,
    hamstring_curl_involved = X10,
    hamstring_curl_LSI = X11,
    leg_press_uninvolved = X13,
    leg_press_involved = X14,
    leg_press_LSI = X15)
 

write.csv(final, "the_data_i_painstakingly_extracted_using_r.csv",row.names=FALSE, na="NA")
